    <title>Combined summary - Planned Obsolescence</title>
    <updated>2023-06-11T20:57:41.872640+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2016-December/013379.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin community has been discussing the issue of how to encourage users to update their node versions. The lack of incentive for people to run full nodes and upgrade their clients is a major issue that has not been discussed enough. One suggestion was to introduce planned obsolescence in each new version of Bitcoin Core, where non-upgraded nodes would stop working after a year. However, there are concerns about the potential for anti-features to be removed by users. Another solution suggested is to stop supporting older versions as developers have limited resources and rarely fix bugs for very old versions.There are also concerns about exploitable and eclipsable nodes, with suggestions to introduce a grace period before disconnecting obsolete nodes. After a grace period, obsolete nodes should still connect and transmit blockheaders, but stop sending full-blocks and transactions to alert the operator that something is wrong and prompt them to upgrade. Finding the right balance between security updates and user autonomy remains a challenge for the Bitcoin community.To address this issue, several ideas have been proposed. One is to implement a message system that would notify users of available updates and the potential risks they face if they don't upgrade. Another idea was to automatically distribute patches and updates, making the process easier for users. However, it was noted that automatic upgrades are not desirable in all cases. Developers have limited resources and are unlikely to give support for older versions.Furthermore, the size of the Bitcoin network in terms of full nodes is decreasing rapidly, which makes it difficult to consider it a decentralized p2p network. Despite proposals to reward those running full nodes, few have been implemented or even considered. Satoshi predicted centralized full nodes, but this contradicts the idea of a decentralized immutable system. Finally, it's important for users to report bugs as they won't get fixed if not reported. One Bitcoin developer, Matt Corallo, has urged people to report bugs to the Bitcoin Github repository. Lack of Python 3 dependency on older CentOS builds could be a reason for node operator's lack of client upgrades.</summary>
